    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-07-04T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-07-04T12:00:00-05:00" n="515"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d515">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1/1093: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hull</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-07-04T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 4, 1933—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 4—11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>100. For the President. Supplementary to my 99, July 4, 3 p.m. (<hi rend="italic"
                        >a</hi>) I would appreciate your indicating your position with regard to die
                    following two questions: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The Conference is probably determined to adjourn in the light of this.
                            Do you wish the delegation to oppose adjournment?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Do you or do you not agree that it is in the American interest at this
                            time to agree to a recess of the Conference?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>This is the alternative plan to adjourn as contemplated by MacDonald and the five
                    gold countries and a number of other central European countries. The plan
                    provides for the permanent sitting of appropriate committees to conduct valuable
                    work pertaining to both the economic and monetary groups of problems. These
                    committees would work under the direction of the Bureau or Steering Committee
                    composed of 14 representatives of the 14 most important governments presided
                    over by Prime Minister MacDonald who would continue the directing head of the
                    interim work.</p>
                <p>The full Conference would be convened some weeks or months later on the call of
                    the President or Prime Minister MacDonald.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
